<rss version="2.0"><channel><title>守护者</title><description>卫报全文RSS。获取更多全文RSS：https://feedx.net</description><link/> https://theguardian.com <item><title><![CDATA[South Africa holds state funeral for divisive Zulu politician Mangosuthu Buthelezi]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/sep/16/south-africa-holds-state-funeral-for-divisive-zulu-politician-mangosuthu-buthelezi]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-16T16:55:00Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/73589a19a05eecd1d549776eaa75df4b4d676cc0/0_34_1032_619 /master/1032.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=861c15af38934b4d5e08cad95f216dc8&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;南非 Mangosuthu Buthelezi 的官方葬礼&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;数千名哀悼者聚集在南非东部周六在乌伦迪镇为资深政治家和祖鲁王子举行国葬&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/sep/10/mangosuthu-buthelezi-obituary&quot;>;Mangosuthu Buthelezi&lt;/a >;.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;布特莱齐，由于与非洲人国民大会 (ANC) 的激烈竞争，在种族隔离解放斗争中成为一个有争议的人物，&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/ 2023/sep/09/zulu-prince-and-veteran-south-african-politician-mangosuthu-buthelezi-dies-ages-95&quot;>;上周去世，享年 95 岁。&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;创始人因卡塔自由党 (IFP) 的成员在与执政的非国大对手纳尔逊·曼德拉和解后，在种族隔离后的政府中担任了两届内政部长。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;当布特莱齐决定言归于好时，在他的支持者和非国大支持者之间的战斗中，2万人被杀，数十万人逃离家园，批评者因此将祖鲁王子称为军阀。&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;相关：&lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2023/sep/16/margaret-thatcher-mangosuthu-butthelezi-south-africa-warlord&quot;>;撒切尔不在乎布特莱齐给南非造成大规模流血事件，但我们不能忘记|克里斯·麦克格雷尔&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;一群 IFP 支持者唱着斗争时代的歌曲并高呼：“他是&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“今天不是指责和指责的日子，”拉马福萨说道，随后布特莱齐的棺材被抬出来，上面覆盖着国旗，鸣放了 21 响礼炮。 “让我们展望未来……关注让我们团结在一起的事物。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;一些哀悼者穿着由豹皮和其他动物皮制成的传统祖鲁服装，手持牛皮制成的盾牌。南非媒体报道称，作为仪式准备工作的一部分，两只长颈鹿和六只黑斑羚被宰杀并剥皮。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Buthelezi 于 1975 年创立了 IFP，并成为现在夸祖鲁-纳塔尔省的主导力量。与非国大一样，布特莱齐也批评白人少数统治，这种统治将祖鲁人和其他南非黑人国家降级为缩小规模的“家园”。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;但他的祖鲁民族主义运动在非洲人国民大会上卷入了与非国大的血腥冲突。 20 世纪 80 年代和 90 年代。非国大由竞争对手科萨民族的成员主导，其领导人认为布特莱齐断断续续地愿意与种族隔离当局合作是对所有南非黑人的背叛。&lt;/p>; &lt;figure data-media-id=&quot;60a8d215f2df7ae07d589a12f5b47937f534c434 &quot;>; &lt;img src=&quot;https://media.guim.co.uk/60a8d215f2df7ae07d589a12f5b47937f534c434/0_53_1600_960/1000.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;前南非总统塔博·姆贝克和南非总统西里尔·拉马福萨（右）出席官方葬礼曼戈苏图·布特莱齐。” width=&quot;1000&quot; height=&quot;600&quot;>; &lt;figcaption>; &lt;span>;南非前总统塔博·姆贝克和南非总统西里尔·拉马福萨（右）出席 Mangosuthu Buthelezi 的官方葬礼。&lt;/span>; &lt;span>;照片：Anadolu Agency/Getty Images&lt;/span>; &lt;/figcaption>; &lt;/figure>; &lt;p>;当布特莱齐决定参加南非 1994 年选举时，两党达成了和平，这是自白人少数统治结束以来的首次全国大选，曼德拉在这次选举中获胜夸祖鲁-纳塔尔省成为祖鲁人前总统雅各布·祖马的大本营，在几起腐败丑闻后，拉马福萨的非国大派系将其驱逐。祖马否认有任何不当行为。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“（布特莱齐）不是一个对紧迫问题置之不理的人……但他了解我们在重建这个国家时面临的巨大困难，”拉马福萨说。 “他……捍卫了我们的民主秩序机构。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;这位祖鲁族酋长于 2019 年辞去了 IFP 领导人的职务。他于 7 月份接受了背痛手术，但后来因背痛没有消退而再次入院。 .&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 17 Sep 2023 01:22:02 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Rory Stewart hits out at ‘incompetence’ in UK government]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2023/sep/16/rory-stewart-hits-out-at-incompetence-in-uk-government]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-16T15:32:11Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/a68acffb353c97919c3a9157f1c769a53bdd23ac/0_331_3291_1974 /master/3291.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=8c698700cbeb67e8740f71e434cc8ac8&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;罗里·斯图尔特&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;&lt;a href=&quot;x-gu://list/mobile. Guardianapis.com/international/lists/tag/politics/rory-stewart&quot;>;罗里·斯图尔特&lt;/a>;在一篇严厉的文章中批评了英国政府的无能，他在文章中将自己和其他人描述为“荒唐地不合格”。 &lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2023/sep/16/rory-stewart-tory-mp-decade-incompetent&quot;>;《卫报周六》的一篇文章&lt;/a>; 杂志前国际发展大臣表示，他的许多议会同事在英国退欧谈判期间并不理解关税同盟的含义。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;斯图尔特，在 2019 年离开下议院之前曾担任保守党领袖，在意识到许多议员计划在 2019 年支持鲍里斯·约翰逊后，分享了他的恐惧。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“这比之前的任何事情都让我震惊。从政九年已经令人沮丧地认识到英国政治缺乏严肃性。”他写道。 “将像鲍里斯·约翰逊这样自负的投机者置于一个已经失去尊严、克制和严肃性的体系的核心，会招致灾难。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;斯图尔特在担任外交大臣时曾与约翰逊共事，他说，他亲眼目睹了自己如何“通过一个不小心的电话破坏了肯尼亚选举的微妙关系”。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;斯图尔特对约翰逊在选举中缺乏能力和关心感到沮丧。英国脱欧谈判，写道：“我发现他不理解自己的脱欧提议，也不在乎。更糟糕的是，我了解到他正在与保守党和英国政治中最具分裂性的势力结盟。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;斯图尔特最近出版了一本回忆录，描绘了他在议会的十年，他谴责了部长级的快乐- 轮换制度，尽管他缺乏专业知识，但在三年多一点的时间里担任了五次不同的部长职务。 “我发现我们很多人，包括我自己，都没有资格担任我们所获得的职位。我被任命负责英格兰和威尔士的所有监狱，但对监狱、监狱管理局、法律或缓刑一无所知。”他写道。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;他还描述了莉兹·特拉斯 (Liz Truss) 的询问，当时的环境他写道，部长在上任第一周就为国家公园制定了一项 10 点计划，“从而表明，所谓的政策只不过是旨在给人以活力假象的新闻稿”。&lt;/p >; &lt;p>;在他的文章中，他还描绘了自金融危机以来地缘政治和经济格局如何发生了根本性变化，他承认，在很多方面，他也未能理解世界正在如何随着自由全球秩序的假设而发生变化。这位前政治家现在是非政府组织 GiveDirectly 的主席，并与托尼·布莱尔 (Tony Blair) 的前通讯主管阿拉斯泰尔·坎贝尔 (Alastair Campbell) 一起主持一个受欢迎的播客。自 2022 年 3 月推出以来，两人讨论和辩论国家政治和国际事务的《The Rest Is Politics》已成为英国最大的播客之一。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;早些时候周，&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/society/2023/sep/10/some-mps-came-close-to-suicide-says-ex-tory-minister-rory-stewart&quot;>;这位前部长表示，在他在议会期间，一些议员同事差点自杀，并描述了政治如何给人们带来“几乎不可持续”的压力。他告诉英国新闻，他“最终鄙视了自己”，因为他在下议院期间试图提升自己的职业生涯。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;在 &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com 中/books/2023/sep/04/politics-on-the-edge-by-rory-stewart-review-blistering-insider-portrait-of-a-nation-in-decline&quot;>;作者在回忆录中的注释&lt;/a >;，边缘政治：内部回忆录&lt;em>;，&lt;/em>;斯图尔特承认他的前同事会对他分享他们的私人谈话感到愤怒，但他认为只有透明度才能弥补“可耻的状态”，从而证明了这一点” 议会已经屈服了。&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 17 Sep 2023 00:22:01 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[One-year-old dies at New York City daycare and three children hospitalized]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/sep/16/child-daycare-death-new-york-city]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-16T15:39:01Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/023ee5eab14b9ff653d454886f4edc109411c0a1/0_219_6000_3600 /master/6000.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=bf3d1271f47086455620390e0439482e&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;纽约警察局汽车&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;一名一岁男孩死亡，另外三名儿童入院治疗急救人员对纽约一家日托中心发生心脏骤停的报告做出回应当局称，周五，市&lt;/a>;。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;警方表示，他们在布朗克斯的家庭日托中心发现了经常用于生产非法药物的设备。据&lt;a href=&quot;https://abc7ny.com/ 报道，警方表示，他们正在调查死亡儿童和住院儿童长期接触某种阿片类药物的可能性。 bronx-daycare-incident-day-care/13789889/&quot;>;WABC&lt;/a>; 和 &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.nytimes.com/2023/09/15/nyregion/bronx-daycare-child- Death.html?smid=nytcore-ios-share&amp;amp;referringSource=articleShare&quot;>;纽约时报&lt;/a>;。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;尽管如此，警方表示有关死亡和住院的原因仍在调查中。&lt; /p>; &lt;p>;当地时间下午 2.40 左右，官员们在 Divino Niño&lt;em>; &lt;/em>;日托中心了解到了紧急情况。他们了解到那里的孩子们已经吃过饭、睡过午觉，当工作人员去叫醒他们时，其中一些孩子仍然昏迷不醒。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;其中一名孩子，名叫尼古拉斯·多米尼奇 (Nicholas Dominici)，被宣布死亡。另外两人（一名两岁男孩和一名八个月大的女孩）被送往医院。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;被送往医院的第三个孩子 - 另一名两岁男孩 -他早些时候从日托中心回家，但因昏昏欲睡、反应迟钝而被送往医生处。据 WABC 报道，阿片类药物逆转药物纳洛酮 (Narcan) 救了他的命。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;消防部门官员测试了空气中是否存在一氧化碳等环境危害，但没有发现任何证据。据 WABC 报道，调查人员随后获得搜查日托中心的搜查令，发现了所谓的公斤压机。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“这是毒贩在包装大量毒品时常用的物品。 ”，纽约警察局侦探局长约瑟夫·肯尼 (Joseph Kenny) 在新闻发布会上说道。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;纽约市卫生专员阿什温·瓦桑 (Ashwin Vasan) 博士表示，当局相信这些孩子以某种方式接触到了“强大的病毒”。可以……使接受者中毒的物质”。尽管如此，瓦桑说：“我们还不知道这起案件中发生了什么”。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;警察局长爱德华·卡班也表示，“我们不知道这些婴儿究竟发生了什么。”&lt; /p>; &lt;p>;该市法医计划对多米尼奇进行尸检以确定他的死因。幸存儿童的尿液和血液将被采集，以查明他们接触了什么物质。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;这家日托中心最近通过了市政府的检查。据 WABC 报道，周五，两名经营日托中心的人受到讯问，并可能面临指控。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;正如《泰晤士报》所指出的，在多米尼奇去世之前，另一名&lt;a href=&quot;https://pix11.com /news/local-news/staten-island/death-of-baby-boy-on-staten-island-deemed-a-homicide-nypd/&quot;>;纽约一岁男孩&lt;/a>;死于二月份因芬太尼、乙酰芬太尼和可卡因的组合中毒。史泰登岛男孩的死亡被裁定为他杀。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;与此同时，2021 年 11 月，小说家保罗·奥斯特 (Paul Auster) 10 个月大的孙女死于芬太尼和海洛因中毒。当局指控&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.nytimes.com/2022/04/28/nyregion/daniel-auster-dead-arrest-overdose.html&quot;>;女孩的父亲&lt;/a>;犯有过失杀人罪，他在案件悬而未决期间死于药物过量。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;em>;美联社提供了报道。&lt;/em>;&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 16 Sep 2023 23:52:02 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Russell Brand accused of rape, sexual assault and emotional abuse]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2023/sep/16/russell-brand-accused-of-sexual-assault-and-emotional-abuse]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-16T15:17:15Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/288e1b8687489795ebc6068725426334ddf91d2e/0_541_3332_1999 /master/3332.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=d69c138134ce660f9c30b5cafafb1c3e&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;拉塞尔·布兰德的头部和肩部照片&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;媒体名人拉塞尔·布兰德被指控强奸在他声名鼎盛的七年期间，性侵犯和精神虐待。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;这些指控是《星期日泰晤士报》、《泰晤士报》和第 4 频道快报联合调查的结果。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>; >; &lt;p>;这位演员兼喜剧演员已经开始否认他所说的“&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2023/sep/16/russell-brand-posts-video-online-周五晚上否认-未指定-刑事指控“非常严重的刑事指控”&lt;/a>;。在网上发布的视频中，布兰德表示，他收到了一家媒体公司和一家报纸的来信，详细介绍了这些说法；这是准备报道有关指定实体的严重指控的记者的标准做法。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;他在多个媒体平台上的帐户中发布的视频中否认了这一说法，坚称他的关系始终是双方自愿的。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>; >; &lt;figure data-atom-id=&quot;68186bf5-788c-4865-bd6a-16ee1fcf00d9&quot; data-atom-type=&quot;media&quot;>; &lt;div>; &lt;div style=&quot;font-size:0&quot;>; __YOUTUBE_MEDIA_PLACEHOLDER_68186bf5-788c-4865 -bd6a-16ee1fcf00d9__ &lt;iframe id=&quot;gu-video-youtube-68186bf5-788c-4865-bd6a-16ee1fcf00d9&quot; src=&quot;https://www.youtube-nocookie.com/embed/LwjpyZAOu6g?modestbranding=1&amp;amp;showinfo= 0&amp;rel=0&amp;enablejsapi=1&amp;embed_config=%7B%22disableAds%22%3Atrue%2C%22nonPersonalizedAd%22%3Atrue%2C%22restrictedDataProcessor%22%3Atrue%2C%22adsConfig%22%3A%7B%22adTagParameters%22 %3A%7B%22cmpGdpr%22%3A1%7D%7D%7D&quot;frameborder=&quot;0&quot;allowfullscreen>;&lt;/iframe>; &lt;/div>; &lt;/div>; &lt;/figure>; &lt;p>;他将这些报告描述为“一连串极其恶劣和侵略性的攻击”。他说，这些与他职业生涯中的一段时期有关，当时他“在主流中工作……正如我在我的书中广泛写到的那样，当时我非常非常混乱”。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;布兰德继续说道： “现在，在那段乱交的时期，我所拥有的关系绝对都是双方自愿的。那时我对此总是保持透明，几乎太透明了，现在我也对此保持透明。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“看到透明度转移到犯罪行为上，我绝对否认，这让我产生疑问：是不是？还有另一个议程吗？”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;em>;更多细节&lt;/em>;&lt;em>;很快......&lt;/em>;&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 16 Sep 2023 23:52:02 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Towns were erased’: Libyan reporters on the ‘horrifying, harrowing’ aftermath of floods]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/2023/sep/16/libyan-reporters-floods-journalists-storm]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-16T15:09:39Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/1543bd0289445b644f95d512cdb190aecc2ca943/0_0_4032_3024 /master/4032.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=f911dff3b71d69dcb596153f1c031c2d&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;德尔纳洪水过后，救援队和利比亚红新月会成员在海滩上搜寻尸体.&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;上周初，Mohamed Eljabo 前往利比亚东部省份，途经德尔纳、贝达和苏萨，他所看到的景象被他描述为“难以理解的震惊”。&lt;/p>; &lt;p >;“我以前访问过这些城市，对它们很了解，”他说。 “当我从的黎波里出发时，我希望能找到这些城市。我期待看到社区和城镇。但这些都消失了。已删除。这太可怕了。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Eljabo 是一名来自的黎波里的独立记者，他是上周目睹了现在难以描述且难以处理的场景的众多当地记者之一。 《观察家报》采访了六名记者，他们曾险些死里逃生，经历过失去朋友和亲人的经历，并在现在几乎从地图上消失的地方进行报道。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“最整个经历中令人难以忘怀的部分是风暴给生者留下的伤疤，”埃尔贾博说。 “当我开始撰写报告并与幸存者互动时，他们的脸上充满了恐惧。他们的眼中、脸上的恐惧是显而易见的。有孩子在家人的坟墓前哭泣，并试图爬进坟墓。我从来没有经历过如此痛苦的事情。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;努拉·马哈茂德·哈达德 (Noura Mahmoud al-Haddad) 是距离德尔纳 100 公里的沙哈特市的一名独立记者，她从窗户里看到雨一直下着。 24 小时，导致停电，水充满街道，高度达到城市建筑物的二层楼。&lt;/p>; &lt;figure data-media-id=&quot;ec8fc920ef027179b6f8d17aa704757c290d0125&quot;>; &lt;img src=&quot;https:// /media.guim.co.uk/ec8fc920ef027179b6f8d17aa704757c290d0125/0_32_960_576/500.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;阿尔及利亚民防潜水队周五在德尔纳被洪水淹没的建筑物中进行搜救行动。&quot; width=&quot;500&quot; height=&quot;300&quot;>; &lt;figcaption>; &lt;span>;阿尔及利亚民防潜水队周五在德尔纳被洪水淹没的建筑物中进行搜救行动。&lt;/span>; &lt;span>;照片：Anadolu Agency/盖蒂图片社&lt;/span>; &lt;/figcaption>; &lt;/figure>; &lt;p>;“这是一个灾难性的夜晚。我们差点被淹死。我什至在我的脸书页面上发布了我的结局，并在睡觉前向我的家人告别。 “我以为我会和我的三个孩子一起死，所以我把他们放在我旁边的床上。”哈达德说。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;洪水对德尔纳和周边地区造成了严重破坏，在海滩、街道和地下留下了尸体。瓦砾。据联合国称，担心疾病传播的地方当局匆忙将 1,000 人掩埋在万人坑中。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;世界卫生组织和其他组织不得不对这种匆忙行为发出警告，称不存在额外的疾病威胁但清洁饮用水是当务之急，因为水会受到污染。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;人们还担心未引爆的炸药会被洪水转移，自内战以来，利比亚已造成 3,457 人死亡据《地雷和集束弹药监测》报道。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;利比亚红新月会表示，德尔纳已有 11,000 人死亡，10,000 多人失踪。救援人员不得不在泥浆中挖掘以寻找更多尸体，同时正在缓慢疏散剩余居民。虽然利比亚西部由联合国支持的政府控制，但利比亚东部的受影响地区在过去十年的大部分时间里一直由军阀哈利法·哈夫塔尔将军统治。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;对于经历过并报道过的记者来说洪水、血腥的政治斗争导致该国的服务质量下降，其中包括 20 世纪 70 年代德尔纳大坝崩溃后缺乏维护。他们和灾区的其他人一样，对如何允许发生如此规模的灾难感到愤怒。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“我在为当地和国际媒体报道事件时试图保持中立并描述情况准确。但我不太确定自己是否能够做到这一点。”来自利比亚东部最大城市班加西的独立记者亨迪亚·哈姆迪·阿拉什皮 (Hendia Hamdy Alashepy) 说道。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;试图澄清一些混乱的责任最终落到实处。落在 Ahrar 利比亚电视频道记者穆罕默德·古尔吉 (Mohamed Gurj) 的肩上，他建立了一个 WhatsApp 群组，将记者彼此以及政府官员联系起来。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;一位经验丰富的记者，他认为自己见过自2011年内战爆发以来的一切，甚至当年还被武装团体绑架，洪水造成的破坏震惊了古尔吉，他决心采取行动。但他发现管理该组织以及平民与官员之间的紧张关系令人难以承受。&lt;/p>; &lt;figure data-media-id=&quot;11dc44be44eeb0960c161ced16f1e45b85c5de1a&quot;>; &lt;img src=&quot;https://media.guim.co.uk /11dc44be44eeb0960c161ced16f1e45b85c5de1a/0_86_4032_2419/1000.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;周六德尔纳被毁房屋的鸟瞰图。&quot; width=&quot;1000&quot; height=&quot;600&quot;>; &lt;figcaption>; &lt;span>;周六德尔纳被毁房屋的鸟瞰图。&lt;/span>; &lt;span>;摄影：Zohra Bensemra/Reuters&lt;/span>; &lt;/figcaption>; &lt; /figure>; &lt;p>;“我发现自己以某种方式负责管理发生的危机，连接各方之间的关系，管理灾难和所有团队。这样压了一天半，我在家就崩溃了，晕了过去。自危机开始以来，我没有吃过任何东西，也没有睡过觉。”Gurj 说道。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;他的妻子 Zainab Jibril 也是一名记者，她一直在试图联系失踪的朋友。 “终于传来消息，我的大多数朋友都安然无恙。他们设法生存下来，但失去了家人。我的朋友们活了下来，但他们回来时已经变成了不同的人。与震惊的严重程度不同。”吉布里勒说道。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;尽管古尔吉亲眼目睹了这场悲剧，但他表示，通过 WhatsApp 群组所做的工作帮助拯救了生命并传达了利比亚的需求，他对此感到自豪。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>; p>; &lt;p>;现在向该国提供的帮助形式是这些利比亚记者的想法，他们在战争时期和敌对政府甚至在洪水之前就报道了该国的问题。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;他们不太关心粮食和援助的短期需求，但表示利比亚需要重建方面的帮助。哈达德说，对于不想离开这座城市的德尔纳人民来说，重建被摧毁的水坝是当务之急，而埃尔贾博则表示需要专业知识。&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;相关： &lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/sep/16/second- humanarian-crisis-feared-in-wake-of-libya-floods-as-hopes- of-finding-survivors-fade&quot;>;利比亚洪水：随着寻找幸存者的希望破灭，调查开始&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;“今天的利比亚人不需要资源。我们有很多。我们需要的是专业知识——技术经验和训练有素的救援人员。我们需要世界派遣经验丰富的救援人员和熟练的专家。我们需要世界向我们伸出援助之手。”他说。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;利比亚的复苏情况将由那些不得不经历风暴的利比亚记者进行报道，比如驻德尔纳的记者 Moataz el-Hasi ，从那以后他几乎没有吃过东西，也没有说话，他的脑海中回放着他所目睹的场景。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“但这是我们的工作，我将在几个小时内回到现场，因为这是我们至少能做到的他说：“向世界展示利比亚正在经历的事情，让他们知道他们可以如何提供帮助。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;这些感言是由 &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.egab.co/ 收集的“ title=&quot;&quot;>;Egab&lt;/a>;，一个与中东和非洲当地记者合作的组织&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 16 Sep 2023 23:22:01 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Lauren Boebert says she ‘fell short of values’ after Beetlejuice groping video]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/sep/16/lauren-boebert-apology-beetlejuice-video]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-16T14:35:53Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/9dfc72f4093e0479ef1f4bb757917e48c49d0bc1/0_137_4987_2992 /master/4987.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=be426ed88ff130f9c763d2031c183cdd&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;劳伦·博伯特。&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;美国国会女议员劳伦·博伯特在被赶出国会后发表道歉&lt;a href=&quot;x-gu://list/mobile.guardianapis.com/international/lists/tag/us-news/denver&quot;>;丹佛&lt;/a>;音乐剧 Beetlejuice 的表演，因行为不当，一种体验她称“很难相处且令人羞愧”。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;科罗拉多州共和党代表博伯特和一名陪同她的男嘉宾&lt;a href=&quot;https://amp.theguardian.com/us-news/2023 /sep/13/lauren-boebert-kicked-out-beetlejuice&quot;>;9 月 10 日被逐出音乐剧&lt;/a>;，原因是在周日演出期间吸电子烟、录制视频和打扰其他观众。视频还显示，他们在座位上急切地互相抚摸。&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;相关：&lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/us-news /2023/sep/13/lauren-boebert-kicked-out-beetlejuice&quot;>;劳伦·博伯特：国会女议员因“造成骚乱”而被踢出音乐剧&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;博伯特和她的竞选活动经理最初否认她吸电子烟，并表示她因声音太大而被解雇。但监控视频&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.9news.com/article/news/local/local-politics/lauren-boebert-vaping-beetlejuice/73-92c1dd6d-714d-4989-b734-08b67ec87817&quot;>;获得丹佛电视台 9News 报道称，这位女议员在表演期间公开吸电子烟。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;两位消息人士也向 9News 证实，Boebert 正在吸电子烟，这是一种被禁止的行为，引座员多次试图向她提出这一问题。 &lt;/p>; &lt;p>;据报道，一名孕妇与 Boebert 面对面，要求女议员停止吸电子烟，&lt;a href=&quot;https://nypost.com/2023/09/15/colorado-rep-lauren-boebert- Called-据《纽约邮报》报道，孕妇在被甲虫汁扔掉之前很痛苦。但博伯特拒绝了。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“我们面前的这些人太无耻了，”这位不愿透露姓名的女士对《华盛顿邮报》说。 “我以前从未见过有人这样做。”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/laurenboebert/status/1701737633292939484?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw%7Ctwcamp%5Etweetembed% 7Ctwterm%5E1701737633292939484%7Ctwgr%5E23532853a1770b8cdeeb4ae84c9423d159c10c55%7Ctwcon%5Es1_&amp;ref_url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.9news.com%2Farticle%2Fnews%2Flocal%2 Flocal-politics%2Flauren-boebert-vaping-beetlejuice%2F73-92c1dd6d-714d- 4989-b734-08b67ec87817&quot;>;闭路电视视频&lt;/a>;还显示，博伯特的客人在就座观看音乐表演后抚摸着她的乳房。人们还看到博伯特在场馆里抚摸客人的胯部，该场馆的顾客通常包括儿童及其家人。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;博伯特和她的约会对象后来在音乐剧的第二幕中被保安带走，因为他们的破坏行为仍在继续。&lt; /p>; &lt;p>;闭路电视录像显示，当博伯特被护送出剧院时，她向剧院保安做出了一个模糊的手势。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;根据剧院保安的对峙报告，据报道，博伯特和她的客人成为了与官员争论。 “你知道我是谁吗？”据剧院安全报告称，这位女议员据称是这么问的。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;博伯特在周五晚上的一份声明中为自己的行为道歉。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“过去的几天是艰难而令人羞愧的，我“我对周日晚上在丹佛给社区带来的不必要的关注感到非常抱歉，”博伯特在道歉中说道，&lt;a href=&quot;https://coloradosun.com/2023/09/15/lauren-boebert-apology -beetlejuice/&quot;>; 据《科罗拉多太阳报》报道&lt;/a>;。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Boebert 补充道，她的“公开而艰难的离婚”给我和我的整个家庭带来了“充满挑战的个人时间”。&lt;/ p>; &lt;p>;“我已尽力以力量和优雅来处理它，但我在周日没有达到我的价值观，”Boebert 说。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Boebert &lt;a href=&quot; https://coloradosun.com/2023/05/16/lauren-boebert-divorce-filing/&quot;>;五月与丈夫 Jayson 申请离婚&lt;/a>;。这对夫妇已经结婚近 20 年了。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;周二，博伯特对音乐剧的干扰首次得到证实，尽管这位女议员最初试图暗示她因太喜欢表演而被逐出剧院。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>; p>; &lt;p>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://x.com/laurenboebert/status/1701737633292939484?s=20&quot;>;在 X&lt;/a>;（以前称为 Twitter）上，Boebert 写道，她“[承认]有罪”笑声和歌声太大声了！”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;这位科罗拉多州女议员在 2022 年以微弱优势连任后，正处于第二个任期。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;她是美国最右翼的代表之一。国会，因她针对 &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2022/nov/24/lauren-boebert-lgbtq-hypocrisy-club-shooting-colorado&quot; 发表的偏执言论而闻名>;LGBTQ+ 人群&lt;/a>;、&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2021/nov/26/ilhan-omar-lauren-boebert-anti-muslim-bigotry&quot;>;穆斯林&lt; /a>; 和其他边缘化社区。&lt;/​​p>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 16 Sep 2023 22:52:01 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[A smoking quill? Notes in Bible margin could be handwriting of the Venerable Bede]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/books/2023/sep/16/bible-margin-father-english-history-venerable-bede-manuscript]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-16T14:15:43Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/bd3b0ce29ffe8d80accbe07259cdcca9761efb19/0_145_564_338 /master/564.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=ea6bb4cd3274cf9566c0c22857c4ee56&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;林迪斯法恩福音书中圣约翰福音的摘录，将 Bede 的翻译纳入古英语 - 以及 Michelle Brown 认为的内容神学家本人的旁注。&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;他通过学术而服务的一生为他赢得了“可敬的”称号。他被认为是后罗马世界最有影响力的思想家之一，并被认为是东正教、天主教和英国圣公会传统中的圣人。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;现在，一位顶尖学者相信她已经找到了手迹的例子被尊为英国历史之父的中世纪神学家比德的作品，以及他“失落”的圣约翰福音古英语译本。&lt;/p>; &lt;figure data-media-id=&quot;cf7bddd6a0431ad08774f5db305d5929f6750d38&quot;>; &lt;img src=&quot; https://media.guim.co.uk/cf7bddd6a0431ad08774f5db305d5929f6750d38/0_0_3000_5988/501.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;诺福克郡布莱克尼圣尼古拉斯教堂的彩色玻璃窗描绘了可敬的比德。&quot; width=&quot;501&quot; height=&quot;1000&quot;>; &lt;figcaption>; &lt;span>;诺福克郡布莱克尼圣尼古拉斯教堂的彩色玻璃窗描绘了可敬的比德。&lt;/span>; &lt;span>;照片：ASP Religion/Alamy&lt;/span >; &lt;/figcaption>; &lt;/figure>; &lt;p>;大英图书馆前插图手稿馆长米歇尔·布朗 (Michelle Brown) 告诉《观察家报》，两份手稿中的大量证据令人信服且令人兴奋，可以将它们与纽卡斯尔附近威尔茅斯和贾罗修道院的八世纪僧侣和学者。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;《阿米亚提努斯手抄本》中《诸王之书》的序言——一本 715 年从贾罗带到罗马的圣经，现在在佛罗伦萨的一个档案馆中——她在带注释的段落和比德出版的著作中发现了语法和语言学之间的相似之处。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;注意到一位杰出学者而不是单纯的抄写员的复杂性，她在书中挑出了复杂的希腊字母形式边距和比德首创的独特的“闪电”来突出引文。&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;她说：“我们知道比德懂希腊语。当时懂希腊语的人并不多。这样我们就得到了旁注和他标记的方式。 The little zigzag lines that look like lightning flashes he invented like a yellow magic marker to indicate when he was quoting a passage – a passage of the Old Testament period in the New Testament, for example. So it&#39;s got these mark-ups that he&#39;s only inventing around this period.”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;She argued that the use of Greek and Hebrew, as well as marginal reference annotations, reflect Bede&#39;s interests and practices: “We also know from his own admission that he was &#39;author, notary and scribe&#39; and would have mastered the gamut of the Insular system of scripts, as this hand had.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“He was referring to the Old Testament use of the word scribe as a priestly function for writing scripture … Given that Codex Amiatinus … [was] such an incredible intellectual feat, it is unthinkable that Bede&#39;s hand would not be present.”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;She added that a number of the scribes left colophons – publisher&#39;s emblems – at the end of their contributions which say, “Pray for me”. “But the one that I think is Bede doesn&#39;t … He emphasises in his colophon, &#39;labore&#39; (work), and that&#39;s something that throughout his autobiographical writings and elsewhere Bede always stresses – the sanctity of the work. So the colophon sections by this particular hand point to a different take … than that of the other scribes.”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;On his deathbed in 735, Bede translated the Gospel of St John into Old English, the first time that a western vernacular language other than Latin had been used to record any part of the Bible.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The original work has not survived but Brown argues that sections were added to the Lindisfarne Gospels around 950, as she has identified evidence such as “characteristic Bedan marginal quotation marks”.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;She also noted the omission of disciples, such as Thomas, that are given in the Latin text, and the addition of the names of the sons of Zebedee, though they are not given in the text: “It seems more consistent with Bede&#39;s rapid translation work, introducing some short cuts due to pressure of time, with death approaching fast, and interpolating some details from memory.”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Brown, who worked at the British Library for 28 years, is professor emerita of medieval manuscript studies at the School of Advanced Study, University of London.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;She said of the evidence: “You haven&#39;t got a smoking quill. It doesn&#39;t say &#39;Bede&#39;. But put all the evidence together and I think this is as good an argument as has been advanced.”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Her discoveries will feature in a new book, titled &lt;em>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://reaktionbooks.co.uk/work/bede-and-the-theory-of-everything&quot; title=&quot;&quot;>;Bede and the Theory of Everything&lt;/a>;&lt;/em>;, to be published by Reaktion Books in October.&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 16 Sep 2023 22:22:01 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Donald Trump pleased at praise from Putin: ‘I like that he said that’]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/sep/16/donald-trump-putin-praise-nbc-interview]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-16T13:55:23Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/f0551c8c617b5c0dd5b95eb0bc5dfda381a52a6a/0_27_4730_2837/master/4730.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=f0fa169f4b453f1a3448b0e10c15285c&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;trump and putin at a podium&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;&lt;a href=&quot;x-gu://list/mobile.guardianapis.com/international/lists/tag/us-news/donaldtrump&quot;>;Donald Trump&lt;/a>; enjoyed hearing that he had drawn praise from the Russian leader Vladimir Putin, the former US president and frontrunner for the 2024 Republican White House nomination has said.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Told during a recorded interview with the new NBC Meet the Press moderator Kristen Welker that Putin had fawned over his stance on Russia&#39;s invasion of Ukraine, Trump &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/donald-trump/trump-pleased-putins-praise-ukraine-russia-meet-the-press-rcna105298&quot;>;replied&lt;/a>;: “I like that he said that. Because that means what I&#39;m saying is right.”&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;Related: &lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/sep/12/putin-trump-political-persecution-claims&quot;>;Legal action against Trump shows &#39;rottenness&#39; of US politics, says Putin &lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;Trump&#39;s remarks to Welker – which circulated on Friday as NBC promoted her interview with the ex-president, which is scheduled to air on Sunday morning – drew condemnation from some political quarters. In a post on X, formerly known as Twitter, the Republicans against Trump group shared a clip of his comments about Putin to Welker and &lt;a href=&quot;https://twitter.com/RpsAgainstTrump/status/1702820225094168757&quot;>;wrote&lt;/a>; to its nearly half-million followers: “A vote for Trump is a vote against America.”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;One of the overarching themes during Trump&#39;s lone term in the Oval Office centered on Russia&#39;s meddling in the 2016 presidential election which he won.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Putin ahead of Sunday&#39;s interview had endorsed Trump&#39;s repeated boasts that he could bring Russia&#39;s conflict with Ukraine to an end within a matter of hours if he were elected to a second term in the White House.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“Mr Trump says he will resolve all burning issues within several days, including the Ukrainian crisis,” Putin said at an economic forum in Russia recently. “We cannot help but feel happy about it.”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Trump&#39;s boast on that topic have earned him derision from his Republican and Democratic opponents, saying it would require a surrender to demands from Putin, whose forces invaded Ukraine in February 2022. But, in his conversation with Welker, Trump doubled down on his position, saying he would simply get Putin and Ukraine&#39;s president Volodymyr Zelenskiy “into a room and I would get a deal worked out”.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Asked by Welker for specifics on precisely how he would bring a swift conclusion to the war in Ukraine, Trump declined to answer, saying: “If I tell you exactly, I lose all my bargaining chips.”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“I mean, you can&#39;t really say exactly what you&#39;re going to do,” Trump told Welker, according to NBC. “But I would say certain things to Putin. I would say certain things to Zelenskiy.”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Welker noted to Trump that Russian bombs had destroyed maternity wards, and forces under Putin&#39;s command had deliberately attacked civilians. Furthermore, the international criminal court (ICC) in The Hague in March &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/mar/17/vladimir-putin-arrest-warrant-ukraine-war-crimes&quot;>;issued an arrest warrant&lt;/a>; for Putin, accusing him of war crimes in connection with the abduction of Ukrainian children.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“It&#39;s all terrible,” Trump told Welker.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Trump has been facing more than 90 criminal charges across four separate indictments charging him with subversion of the 2020 election that he lost to his Democratic rival Joe Biden, retention of classified information after his presidency, and hush-money payments to adult film star Stormy Daniels.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Civil cases with which he is grappling include a $250m lawsuit by the New York attorney general of his business affairs as well as a defamation claim stemming from a rape accusation that a judge has deemed to be “substantially true”.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Trump nonetheless denies all wrongdoing and has sought to cast himself as the victim of political persecution. He also maintains substantial leads in national and key state polls regarding the 2024 Republican presidential primary.&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 16 Sep 2023 22:22:01 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Leading critic of Egyptian state jailed for six months]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/sep/16/hisham-kassem-leading-critic-egyptian-state-jailed]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-16T14:04:14Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/f86dc37d0e32c34ec9b2bf1a383191fb5a4818b3/0_0_4032_2420/master/4032.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=4ccad3a64619a0e8875d4a2e9f3c7869&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;Hisham Kassem&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;A court in Cairo has sentenced a former newspaper publisher, free speech advocate and rights activist to six months in prison in a trial observers say constitutes an attack on a leading critic of the Egyptian state.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Hisham Kassem, the former publisher of Al Masry Al Youm newspaper, received six months in detention and a fine of 20,000 EGP (approximately £523) for slandering and defaming Kamal Abu Eita. Abu Eita is a former minister and current member of Egypt&#39;s presidential pardon committee, tasked with granting clemency towards some of the tens of thousands of detainees in the Egyptian prison system.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The former publisher was also accused of slandering a public official, and required to pay a further fine of 10,000 EGP (£261) to Abu Eita.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Kassem is a prominent figure in Egyptian journalism and advocacy as well as a leading analyst of the upper echelons of the regime of president Abdel Fatah al-Sisi, long considered untouchable and protected by his status.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;He previously headed the Egyptian Organization for Human Rights, and is currently part of the board of trustees of the liberal Free Current movement, a coalition of opposition figures and parties whose &lt;a href=&quot;https://apnews.com/article/egypt-elsissi-government-dissent-7231c03b42104e32fb5b9285c7cc0174&quot;>;spokesman recently said&lt;/a>; Sisi&#39;s governance represented “a severe danger to the political and economic future of our country.”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;In the three weeks since Kassem was detained over his comments on X, formerly Twitter, critics have pointed to the opaque charges levelled at him with confusion. Following his detention in a Cairo police station in mid August, he was referred to trial on charges of slandering Abu Eita. Kassem was then brought before prosecutors the following day, and told that police at the station where he had been held overnight also accused him of verbally assaulting them, charges he strenuously denied.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The Egyptian Initiative for Personal Rights &lt;a href=&quot;https://eipr.org/en/press/2023/08/arbitrary-pretrial-detention-used-punish-opposition-figure-hisham-kassem&quot;>;said&lt;/a>; the accusations against Kassem were an effort to target him for his “political activity and for using his right to express his opinion”. Similar charges of slander and disturbing public officials, the organisation said, are increasingly being used “as a pretext to target political opponents, writers, journalists, and content creators on social media platforms”.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Kassem&#39;s detention, according to one leading Egyptian rights activist who requested anonymity for their own safety, represents a watershed.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“They&#39;re trying to make an example out of him,” they said. “These charges show the intention of the regime to silence Hisham Kassem and to set an example for anyone who dares raise their voice against Sisi.”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Kassem&#39;s role in publishing Al Masry Al Youm, one of Egypt&#39;s lone private sources of media when it was founded in 2004, was “a game changer”, they added.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“It was the lifeblood of free speech, it changed the way we perceived things, it rooted in us that it&#39;s important to say what you think, that you can think differently and it&#39;s fine. Kassem was also a game changer, and I think this is why he was targeted, they don&#39;t want this to happen again.”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Since sweeping to power in a military coup in 2013, Sisi has spearheaded a crackdown on all forms of political dissent and free speech, targeting his opponents in every field of public life. State-backed interests, often with ties to the Egyptian security services, control the vast majority of private media outlets, including Al Masry Al Youm.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Despite growing concern about Egypt&#39;s human rights record, the US opted to withhold $85m in military aid to the north African country last week citing humanitarian concerns, far less than the amount withheld in previous years. A decision on a further $235m is imminent, amid growing pressure from some lawmakers to withhold the maximum possible amount due to Egypt&#39;s deteriorating record on rights, particularly its frequent detention of critics.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Sisi is expected to run for a third term in office next year, if not before, in a vote that is considered a foregone conclusion in his favour before any ballot has been cast.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Activists and critics alike have expressed concern that Kassem&#39;s sentencing represents the first blow in what could be a months-long campaign of added pressure on even the mildest critics before the vote.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“We are expecting an intensification ahead of the elections,” said the rights activist.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Still, they added, “the lack of care by the international community towards Hisham Kassem&#39;s case, it was perceived as a green light by the government. This is very dangerous”.&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 16 Sep 2023 22:22:01 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[Kim Jong-un inspects nuclear-capable aircraft on Russian visit]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/sep/16/kim-jong-un-inspects-nuclear-capable-aircraft-russia-visit]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-16T13:19:43Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/b0899302716d92b1a1e31d46d2bf1e020549c6eb/0_51_910_546/master/910.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=42cfab4fc5620c5f88bebc1e300acf70&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;Kim Jong-un, dressed in a suit, flanked by Sergei Shoigu and another Russian military official, both in uniform, walk across an airfield as a crowd of people follow them&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;The North Korean leader, Kim Jong-un, has inspected Russian nuclear-capable strategic bombers, hypersonic missiles and warships, accompanied by Vladimir Putin&#39;s defence minister.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Sergei Shoigu greeted Kim at Russia&#39;s Knevichi airfield, about 30 miles (50km) from the Pacific port city of Vladivostok, on Saturday. The North Korean leader then inspected a guard of honour.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The US and South Korea fear the revival of Moscow&#39;s friendship with Pyongyang could give Kim access to some of Russia&#39;s sensitive missile technology while helping arm Russia in its war in Ukraine.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Shoigu showed Kimstrategic bombers – the Tu-160, Tu-95 and Tu-22M3 – which are capable of carrying nuclear weapons and form the backbone of Russia&#39;s nuclear air attack force, Russia&#39;s defence ministry said.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“It can fly from Moscow to Japan and then back again,” Shoigu told Kim of one aircraft.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Kim was shown asking how the missiles were fired from the aircraft, at times nodding and smiling.&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;Related: &lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/sep/15/vladimir-putin-kim-jong-un-summit-russia-north-korea-meeting-five-things&quot;>;The Vladimir Putin-Kim Jong-un summit: five things we learned &lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;Shoigu showed him the MiG-31I supersonic interceptor aircraft equipped with Kinzhal air-launched hypersonic missiles, which are capable of carrying nuclear or conventional warheads.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The missile has a reported range of 1,500-2,000km (930-1,240 miles) while carrying a payload of up to 480kg (1,060lbs). It can travel at up to 10 times the speed of sound.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Russia&#39;s ambassador to North Korea, Alexander Matsegora, told reporters that Kim&#39;s schedule was “very intense” and it was not clear how long he would remain in Russia, the Russian state news agency RIA reported.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Kim inspected the Russian Pacific fleet&#39;s frigate Marshal Shaposhnikov in Vladivostok and saw a demonstration of modern missile control systems, RIA said.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;South Korea and the US said on Friday that military cooperation between North Korea and Russia would violate UN sanctions against Pyongyang and that the allies would ensure there was a price to pay.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Russia has gone out of its way to publicise Kim&#39;s visit and drop repeated hints about the prospect of military cooperation with North Korea, which was established in 1948 with the backing of the Soviet Union.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;For Vladimir Putin, who says Moscow is locked in an existential battle with the west over Ukraine, courting Kim allows him to needle Washington and its Asian allies while potentially securing a deep supply of artillery for the Ukraine war.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Washington has accused North Korea of providing arms to Russia, which has the world&#39;s largest number of nuclear warheads, but it is unclear whether any deliveries have been made.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;On Friday, Kim inspected a Russian fighter-jet factory that is under western sanctions.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;He and the Russian president discussed military matters, the war in Ukraine and deepening cooperation when they met on Wednesday. Putin told reporters Russia was “not going to violate anything” but that it would keep developing relations with North Korea.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The Kremlin&#39;s spokesperson, Dmitry Peskov, told reporters there had not been a plan to sign any formal agreements during the visit.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Russian diplomats said Washington had no right to lecture Moscow after the US had bolstered its allies across the world, including with a visit of a US nuclear-armed ballistic missile submarine to South Korea in July.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;While in Vladivostok, Kim watched the first act of the ballet Sleeping Beauty, staged by St Petersburg&#39;s Mariinsky theatre, the RIA news agency reported.&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 16 Sep 2023 21:52:01 +0800</pubDate> </item><item><title><![CDATA[‘You can’t unsee it’: the mental toll of Maui fires on search-and-rescue teams]]></title><link/><![CDATA[https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/sep/16/maui-wildfires-search-and-rescue-workers-mental-health]]><description> &lt;div>;&lt;i>;2023-09-16T11:00:30Z&lt;/i>;&lt;/div>;&lt;div>;&lt;img src=&quot;https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/5724c77a9856cd0b7715e999ffb9dbe2b097d181/0_285_5899_3540/master/5899.jpg?w=600&amp;fit=bounds&amp;sig-ignores-params=true&amp;s=1535e48c1e306a11afc2f90798a2a9c7&quot; alt=&quot;&quot;>;two search and rescue workers and a dog among rubble&lt;/div>;&lt;p>;Walking through the ruins of Lahaina day after day, in between the rubble of destroyed homes and ash-covered streets, Eric Darling would try to remember his motto.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“Everybody comes home,” the retired California firefighter would tell himself. “Including me.”&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;Related: &lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/sep/14/us-forest-service-wildfire-fighters-low-pay&quot;>;Pressure and pay drive exodus of US wildfire fighters: &#39;The fatigue is real&#39;&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;The canine handler had traveled to the island with his dog, Mazie, as part of a Federal Emergency Management Agency team to assist in the grim, yet vital work of recovering human remains. The mission was to search every structure to recover the dead, providing closure to grieving families and answers to the community.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Such a deployment comes with an additional responsibility for Darling and others like him, on the scene and in the years to come: coping with the mental toll of witnessing mass death and destruction. The demands on search-and-recovery teams are increasingly urgent as deadly disasters increase in frequency and magnitude.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Before Maui, Darling had responded to the &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2018/dec/20/last-day-in-paradise-california-deadliest-fire-untold-story-survivors&quot;>;2018 Camp fire&lt;/a>; that eviscerated the town of Paradise and killed 85 people. Two years later, he was a member of the team combing for remains following the &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/dec/30/california-wildfires-north-complex-record&quot;>;North Complex fire&lt;/a>; that killed 16 people.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“Those big ones, they sort of sit with you for a while,” Darling said. “It was a lot of deja vu seeing it again in Maui. The sheer devastation hit me pretty hard.”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The destruction in Lahaina, the historic capital of the Hawaiian kingdom, shocked residents and seasoned emergency personnel alike. The blaze moved with such speed and ferocity that residents, who received no official warning, &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2023/aug/15/lahaina-survivor-hawaii-fires&quot;>;struggled to evacuate&lt;/a>;. The flames wiped away the waterfront community and at least 97 people died. &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/2023/09/15/coming-up-mpd-discuss-latest-number-unaccounted-following-lahaina-fire/&quot;>;Thirty-one&lt;/a>; people are still missing.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;•&lt;/span>;&lt;span>;•&lt;/span>;&lt;span>;•&lt;/span>;&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The work of emergency personnel is what reveals the true toll of deadly disasters. Recovering the dead after a major wildfire is an immense undertaking, requiring hundreds of search and recovery workers, from forensic anthropologists to canine handlers with dogs trained to detect human remains. These teams carefully scour the rubble and in Lahaina some have taken to the sea looking for possible victims.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;For canine handlers like Darling and Heather Ferguson, with a taskforce from Ohio, the days began at about 4am. With their dogs, Mazie, a black labrador, and Melvin, a Belgian malinois, they started their searches just after sunrise and worked from 6am to 6pm.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;In Maui, the dogs navigated a dense stretch of land while their handlers kept an eye out for hazards, like the island&#39;s wild chickens that roamed through the burn area, and tried to determine where one property ended and others began.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“It literally is structure by structure. We&#39;re putting those dogs into whatever is left and allowing them to work that structure and moving them on to the next,” Ferguson said.&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;Related: &lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/jul/19/canada-wildfires-firefighters-shortage&quot;>;&#39;Fighting a losing battle&#39;: waves of wildfires leave Canada&#39;s volunteer firefighters drained&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;If a dog alerts – typically with a bark – a forensic anthropologist will determine whether or not there are human remains present. Building materials and drywall can sometimes resemble human bone, said Colleen Milligan, a forensic anthropologist at California State University Chico, who was deployed to Maui.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Milligan has extensive experience in this area as she and her CSU-Chico team helped in the recovery of &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.anthropology-news.org/articles/forensic-anthropology-in-a-changing-climate/&quot;>;75 of the 85&lt;/a>; victims of the Camp fire, which burned through a neighboring town.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“What struck us was not so much what was different but how much was the same,” she said.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Once human remains are identified, the team pores over the area, typically on their hands and knees with trowels and brushes to recover what they can. They use strains to sift through the debris to collect small teeth, small hand and foot bones, said Eric Bartelink, a CSU-Chico forensic anthropologist who also worked in Maui.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“We don&#39;t want to leave any visible trace of the fire victim behind,” he said.&lt;/p>; &lt;figure data-media-id=&quot;fd67ca921d440b0b155292e5b179b2baff2553b9&quot;>; &lt;img src=&quot;https://media.guim.co.uk/fd67ca921d440b0b155292e5b179b2baff2553b9/0_0_3264_2176/1000.jpg&quot; alt=&quot;Members of a Fema search and rescue taskforce comb through destroyed neighborhoods in Lahaina.&quot; width=&quot;1000&quot; height=&quot;667&quot;>; &lt;figcaption>; &lt;span>;Members of a Fema search and rescue taskforce comb through destroyed neighborhoods in Lahaina.&lt;/span>; &lt;span>;Photograph: FEMA/Reuters&lt;/span>; &lt;/figcaption>; &lt;/figure>; &lt;p>;The work is mentally and physically taxing. In Maui, the long days were humid and hot – ground temperatures in some areas were as high as 160F (71C), teams reported. Dogs wore booties to protect their paws and the animals and their handlers both underwent decontamination at the end of the day.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The sight of so much destruction is surreal, but Ferguson said she tried to focus on the purpose behind the work.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“There&#39;s a reason I do it and the reason I do it is because I can,” Ferguson said. “At the end of the day I know I can help myself and I can help others and I can bring closure to people and that&#39;s why I do it.”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;The weight of that work can linger. Ferguson, an independent handler who works as a toxicologist day to day, said it&#39;s common for her to feel slow and foggy for the first few days after returning from a deployment.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;It helps to have teammates on scene to talk things through during and after the disaster, said Ferguson, whose training in helping to recover the dead has led her to a series of emergencies, from the Florida condo collapse to a tornado in Kentucky and Hurricane Ian.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“At the end of the day, you can&#39;t unsee or unexperience the things that happened in Maui,” she said. “I can still close my eyes and picture walking through some of those places and some of those homes and see those things where maybe my dog alerted.”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Emergency personnel responding to disasters need ongoing support upon their return, said Tim Houweling, who cofounded a non-profit that helps first responders access alternative therapies. Problems don&#39;t always surface immediately, he said, they can come up months or even years after the incident.&lt;/p>; &lt;aside>; &lt;p>;&lt;span>;Related: &lt;/span>;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.theguardian.com/world/2023/jul/11/everyone-loved-angel-spanish-town-still-grieving-for-hero-who-fought-wildfires&quot;>;&#39;Everyone loved Ángel&#39;: Spanish town still grieving for hero who fought wildfires&lt;/a>;&lt;/p>; &lt;/aside>; &lt;p>;“Exposure to 100% destruction is not something the mind can really comprehend,” he said. “A lot of us go into task mode. It&#39;s something that needs to be processed.”&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;While in Maui, Darling quickly put aside his shock and focused on the job and the mission of bringing people home.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;But there are some things you can&#39;t prepare for, he said, like the gratitude residents showed him. As he prepared to board a flight departing Maui, his fellow passengers, some of whom were residents displaced by the fire, began to applaud him. They refused to board the plane before Darling and his dog, Mazie.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;Their praise, while well-meaning, was painful.&lt;/p>; &lt;p>;“I wasn&#39;t expecting that. I felt very small,” he said. “I came out here to do my job. You folks lost family or a business or a residence. I&#39;m going home and you&#39;re seeking shelter in another state.”&lt;/p>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 16 Sep 2023 19:22:01 +0800</pubDate></item></channel></rss>